{"cursor":"9371","size":15,"audio":[],"currentlang":"en","article":"{{Infobox mineral\n| name = Montmorillonite category = Phyllosilicates Smectite group\n| boxwidth = image = Mineraly.sk - montmor.jpg caption = A sample of\n| montmorillonite (unknown scale) formula = (Na,Ca) 0.33 (Al,Mg) 2-\n| (Si 4O 10 )(OH) 2Â·nH 2O symmetry\n| = Monoclinic prismatic H-M symbol: 2/m Space group: C2/m unit cell = a\n| = 5.17 Ã, b = 8.94 Ã, c = 9.95 Ã; Î² = 99.54Â°; Z = 1 color = White, pale pink,\n| blue, yellow, red, green habit = compact masses of lamellar or globular\n| microcrystalline aggregates system = Monoclinic twinning = cleavage = {001}\n| perfect fracture = Uneven tenacity = mohs = 1â2 luster = Dull, earthy streak =\n| diaphaneity = Translucent gravity = 1.7-2 density = polish = opticalprop =\n| Biaxial (-) refractive = n Î± = 1.485â1.535 n Î² =\n| 1.504â1.550 n Î³ = 1.505â1.550 birefringence = Î´ = 0.020 pleochroism\n| = 2V = Measured: 5Â° to 30Â° dispersion = extinction = length fast/slow =\n| fluorescence= absorption = melt = fusibility = diagnostic = solubility = other\n| = alteration = references = [http://www.mindat.org/min-\n| 2821.html Montmorillonite]. Mindat.org [http://webmineral.com/data/Montmorillonite.shtml\n| Montmorillonite]. Webmineral\n}}\n\n'Montmorillonite' is a very soft phyllosilicate group of minerals that typically\nform in microscopic crystals, forming a clay. It is named after Montmorillon in\nFrance. Montmorillonite, a member of the smectite family, is a 2:1 clay, meaning\nthat it has 2 tetrahedral sheets sandwiching a central octahedral sheet. The\nparticles are plate-shaped with an average diameter of approximately one\nmicrometre. Members of this group include saponite.\n\nMontmorillonite is the main constituent of the volcanic ash weathering product,\nbentonite.\n\nThe water content of montmorillonite is variable and it increases greatly in\nvolume when it absorbs water. Chemically it is hydrated sodium calcium aluminium\nmagne